{
  "text": "Antimalarials, antibiotics and analgesics/antipyretics were the most used drugs in the three studies performed in African countries [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Antimalarials accounted for 24% of drugs purchased at pharmacies or drug stores in the Kibaha district, Tanzania [CITATION_4] , while a study performed in Nigeria reported that these drugs were prescribed to 65% of children <5 years old attending an outpatient clinic [CITATION_5] . In these two studies, antibiotics covered 31% of purchased drugs and 54% of patients. Chloroquine was prescribed in 70% of sick-patient visits in health facilities in Kenya, penicillin in 61%, and antipyretics in 59% [CITATION_6] .",
